 lightly influence groups in society to change their behaviour, using behavioural insights to solve complex policy problems. Generally, behavioural approaches focus on the psychology underlying the implementation and effects of policies in practice. First published as a special issue of Policy & Politics journal, this book situates these reforms within a broader tradition of methodological individualism. With contributions from international scholars, it demonstrates that when behavioural policies expand their focus beyond the individual, they have the potential to better understand, investigate, and shape social outcomes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBehaviorism (Political science). 0aPolitical planning. 0aPublic administrationxSocial aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBall, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonvin, Jean-Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButera, Fabrizio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCotterill, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEntwistle, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEwert, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEwert, Benjamin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHead, Brian W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohn, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Don S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoer, Kathrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoer, Kathrin, eeditor.4edt4http://